<TEXT>
the head of new caledonias separatist movement and 
the islands conservative profrench deputy reached agreement early 
sunday on the future of the troubled territory prime minister 
michel rocard announced 
he said that under the accord paris will assume direct control 
of the south pacific territory for the next 12 months with new 
caledonians voting in referendum in 10 years on the issue of 
selfdetermination 
rocard also said he would propose to president francois 
mitterrand that the french people be consulted in a referendum on 
new institutions to be set up to develop the territory 
tensions in new caledonia an island group 1000 miles east of 
australia have remained high 21 people were killed in may when a 
french army assault team stormed a cave to free 23 hostages held by 
native melanesian separatists 
thirty people have died in violence in new caledonia since april 
22 
the accord reached sunday came after negotations in paris 
involving rocard jeanmarie tjibaou head of the kanak socialist 
national liberation front and deputy jacques lafleur 
the kanaks or melanesians represent about 43 percent of the 
new caledonias 145000 residents and most favor independence the 
rest of the population comprises descendents of european settlers 
asians and polynesians most of whom prefer to remain french 
france colonized the islands in 1853 
rocard brought tjibaou and lafleur together last week for their 
first meeting since 1982 he said they both would take the 
agreement to their respective constituencies and call for approval 
tjibaou called the agreement reached sunday an important 
step but said the new caledonia problem has not been solved and 
native melanesians will continue to demand independence 
he said the talks were difficult because the demands of the two 
sides were contradictory and because of the tense atmosphere in the 
territory 
each side now is committed to halt bloodshed and end mourning 
for many families tjibaou said 
a statement issued by rocard called on the territorys 
inhabitants to be hopeful for a new page has been turned not by 
arms but by dialogue and tolerance by hard work and good will 
rocard made a solution to the new caledonia problem a priority 
after mitterrand named him prime minister 45 days ago the 
agreement seems likely to restore some of rocards prestige which 
was tarnished after the socialists failed to win a majority in 
legislative elections that followed the may 8 presidential vote 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

