<TEXT>
worldwide grain stocks could sink to their lowest 
levels of the decade and lead to possible food shortages if the 
crippling us drought continues for another two weeks according 
to a un organization 
but officials at the un food and agriculture organization say 
favorable weather and crop prospects have created a brighter farm 
picture in most of the rest of the world 
before the us drought took hold the romebased un 
organization already was projecting that world grain production in 
198889 would not match consumption and that stocks would drop 
close to the level the agency considers the minimum necessary to 
safeguard world food security 
now with the us drought the question is how much is us 
production going to be drawn down peter newhouse chief of the 
agencys global information and early warning service said in an 
interview friday 
its still too early for firm projections it all depends on 
the rain in the next two weeks he said 
the organization had projected june that the united states would 
produce 279 million tons of this years targeted 167 billion tons 
of grain worldwide but that was before the worst drought since the 
great depression parched the midwest 
if the present dry weather were to continue over the next 
couple of weeks then there would be a severe shortfall in us 
crops particularly maize corn newhouse said we had already 
projected that with normal weather conditions the stocks could 
fall close to the minimum level now if the drought continues 
theres a distinct possibility it could fall below that 
the un organization considers the minimum level to be 17 
percent to 18 percent of the projected global consumption of wheat 
for the following year the last time the level fell to the minimum 
level was in 1981 
stocks have not dropped below the minimum since the mid1970s 
they hit a low of 14 percent during the global food crisis of 
197273 
if stocks go below the mininum level it would mean the world 
is more vulnerable than it should be and could face food supply 
difficulties newhouse said 
weve still got a cushion but if the cushion is going to 
be used up it looks like the food situation on a global level is 
going to be a lot tighter 
newhouse said the organization will have to be very vigilant 
in monitoring us cereal crops and those in asia the soviet union 
and africa 
fortunately harvest prospects outside the united states and 
canada are generally favorable newhouse said 
at this moment we dont see any widespread drought problems 
nothing dramatic said rene gommes of the agencys 
agrometeorological department 
the only country that produces more cereal crops than the united 
states is china with about 350 million tons annually third is the 
soviet union with 200 million tons 
newhouse said harvest prospects were good in the soviet union 
in china drought has hit some areas and floods have hit others 
but at this point were not worried about china he said 
an important factor for world crop production is the monsoon 
season in india bangladesh and pakistan which were hit by severe 
drought last year 
the monsoon started in may on time this year but its still 
far too early to say what will happen newhouse said 
one of the worlds most serious food supply situations is 
occurring partly as a result of heavy rainfall in areas often prone 
to drought conditions swarms of migrating desert locusts who 
breed in rainy conditions have invaded the sahel region of 
subsaharan africa 
the infestation is of unprecedented dimensions and will affect 
the food security of 15 african countries from the atlantic ocean 
to the red sea the un groups directorgeneral edouard 
saouma said friday 
in african countries such as angola mozambique sudan and 
ethiopia civil war has aggravated crop failures in ethiopia 
where drought and famine killed up to 1 million people in 198485 
more than 7 million people are reported threatened by the drought 
and last years crop failures 
the crop planting season is now under way in ethiopia so it 
wont be known until the end of the year whether the country can 
recover newhouse said 
in latin america northeast brazil suffered severe drought last 
year but the weather has improved and newhouse believes the harvest 
will recover mexico however is expecting a shortfall of more 
than 1 million tons in its wheat harvest he said 
</TEXT>
