<TEXT>
the american heart association approved a 
system sunday to identify and endorse processed foods that meet the 
groups dietary guidelines 
the association said it will look mainly at the salt 
cholesterol and fat levels in food products in deciding whether to 
endorse them as hearthealthy items bearing the groups seal 
of approval are expected to reach shelves within a year 
we regard this new initiative as a logical expansion of the 
american heart associations wellestablished role as the publics 
chief advocate and efforts to reduce premature death and 
disability from heart disease and stroke said dr ww aston of 
dallas chairman of the aha task force that studied the product 
approval idea for the past two years 
the first group of foods that will be examined by an independent 
testing group will be margarines cooking oils and salad dressings 
the association does not expect to endorse meats fruits and other 
nonprocessed food items 
the recommendation was made at the annual delegate assembly in 
st louis which began friday and ended sunday there were about 
140 affiliates and scientific counsels represented at the delegate 
assembly the delegates are the policymaking group for the aha 
heart and blood vessel diseases are the nations leading 
killers and took nearly 1 million lives in the united states in 
1985 the most recent year for which statistics are complete the 
aha said nearly 65 million americans have one or more forms of the 
diseases 
members of the task force said sunday that dietary control is 
one of the most effective ways to reduce the risk of cardiovascular 
disease since 1961 the aha has been recommending a diet low in 
fat salt and cholesterol as a way to help reduce heart disease 
many americans have adopted healthier eating habits and 
dietary improvements recommended by the aha clearly have played a 
part in the welcome decline in heart attack and stroke death rates 
that we have seen in the last two decades aston said 
he added that two independent nationwide surveys of consumers 
and health specialists showed that they responded favorably to the 
ahas efforts and wanted more specific information about fat and 
cholesterol levels 
the program will include creation of a consumer health 
information program it will establish a tollfree national 
nutritional telephone hotline that will be staffed by registered 
dietitians who will give information about nutrition and risk 
factors for heart disease to the public and health professionals 
the program also will include media campaigns and a brochure 
listing products that receive the aha stamp of approval the 
brochures will describe the program and provide other facts about 
risk factors with an emphasis on the dangers of cigarette smoking 
and high blood pressure 
</TEXT>
