<TEXT>
nurses are squaring off with the nations largest 
group of doctors for a battle this week over a physicians proposal 
to offset the nursing shortage by creating a new class of bedside 
hospital worker 
doctors attending the american medical associations annual 
policymaking convention which opened sunday will debate a plan to 
establish a new type of lessertrained hospital worker to provide 
some care to patients at bedside 
ama officials believe their plan for registered care 
technologists who would handle such chores as changing bandages 
and taking vital signs would be an innovative step toward easing 
the nations nursing shortage 
but the proposal has drawn harsh criticism from the american 
nurses association which contends the best answer to the shortage 
is to improve working conditions and pay nurses better salaries 
its an impractical poorly thoughtout proposal said mary 
foley a nurse from san francisco and an elected cabinet member for 
the nurses association it could be potentially very dangerous 
she said nurses often help diagnose problems with patients and 
act as a backstop to doctors the technogists wouldnt have the 
expertise to spot medical complications or other problems in a 
patient she said 
lillian joel president of the kansas city mobased 
association representing 188000 nurses plans to testify against 
the proposal during a hearing monday at the ama convention the 
illinois nurses association also has organized a protest rally 
monday morning 
dr william hotchkiss ama president disputed the nurses 
concerns and contended the bedside technologists would give nurses 
more time to perform vital highly technical patientcare 
management tasks 
it is in addition to nurses hotchkiss said we are not 
threatening the nurses in any way we want all the nurses we can 
get 
dr joseph painter an internist from houston said the amas 
board of trustees devised the proposal because the nations 
shortage of nurses is projected to hit 300000 by 1992 
were dealing with a major shortage that doesnt look like it 
will improve painter said we dont see this as a turf problem 
between medicine and nursing our view is the person who is 
really suffering from this acute shortage of bedside care is the 
patient 
the ama wants to test its idea on an experimental basis in 
states that now have the worst shortage of nurses he said 
the boards proposal would create three levels of registered 
care technologists the first an assistant technologist would 
be a high school graduate who could begin working with patients 
after two months training 
the worker could become a full licensed technologist with an 
additional seven months onthejob training with nine months of 
more specialized training the worker would become an advanced 
technologist who could work in critical care units painter said 
we thought it should be an apprenticetype training program 
he said we wanted to appeal to a different type of applicant who 
might not want to spend two to four years in college but who would 
want to earn while they learn 
but ms foley a nurse at st francis memorial hospital in san 
francisco called the proposal misguided 
we do have a crisis right now because there is a shortage of 
nurses but the solution to that is not to create an alternative 
healthcare giver with lesser skills she said 
the proposal also has drawn criticism from within the ama ranks 
the ohio delegation to the convention introduced a resolution to 
scrap the idea contending it would further dilute the pool of 
available individuals for the nursing profession and would increase 
the cost of medical care by creating a new category of health care 
provider 
sunday was an opening session of the house of delegates whose 
420 members act as a policymaking legislature for the 
295000member ama 
dr william hotchkiss of chesapeake va gave his farewell 
speech as outgoing president of the ama saying members must work 
to counter the attitude among a small number of doctors that the 
profession is no longer worth fighting for and is no longer 
worth pursuing as a career 
james sammons the amas executive vice president told the 
convention in a written report that doctors and scientists must be 
prepared to battle animal rights activists trying to ban the use of 
animals in medical research 
im afraid that unless we undertake a massive effort to 
protect biomedical research these people are going to force 
medical science into a choice between experiments on animals and 
experiments on humans sammons said 
