<TEXT>
residents of a disputed region in the southern 
soviet union voted at a public meeting to end a monthlong general 
strike soviet media reported sunday 
the work stoppage began in the nagornokarabakh region on may 23 
to press demands that the predominantly armenian region part of 
the republic of azerbaijan be annexed to neighboring armenia 
the legislature of azerbaijan refused to cede the region and 
the governments of armenia and nagornokarabakh have asked the 
moscowbased supreme soviet legislature to intervene 
however in moscow a soviet deputy justice minister mikhail 
vyshinsky indicated at a news conference sunday that the region 
could not be transferred to armenian control without the consent of 
azerbaijan 
as long as the decision about the transfer of 
nagornokarabakh is not taken by azerbaijan the constitution 
does not allow a change in borders of the territory of a 
republic vyshinsky was quoted by the official tass news agency 
as saying 
nagornokarabakh residents met in the regions administrative 
center stepanakert on saturday night and voted to end the strike 
the communist party daily pravda and radio moscow reported 
on the whole the participants in the meeting took a 
constructive decision to restore the rhythm of work pravda 
said it said a majority had agreed with the decision 
pravda also said some in the crowd had not agreed with a call 
from the head of the regional communist party z movsesyan that 
they renounce the use of strongarm methods as a means to 
pressure authorities into accepting their demands 
participants also rejected a suggestion that they wait until the 
end of a nationwide communist party conference scheduled to begin 
tuesday to see what actions they should take in line with the 
conferences decisions pravda said 
the newspaper did not elaborate but the decision could mean 
that demonstrations are planned in nagornokarabakh during the 
conference the partys first in 47 years 
delegates at the conference are expected to discuss relations 
between the more than 100 ethnic groups in the soviet union 
although the disagreement over nagornokarabakh is not specifically 
on the agenda 
the dispute has sparked huge demonstrations in armenia and 
unrest in azerbaijan officials say 32 people including 26 
armenians and six azerbaijanis were killed in rioting in the 
azerbaijani city of sumgait in late february and early march 
reports also said eight armenians and eight azerbaijanis were 
injured in fights in two armenian villages this month 
the labor daily trud in a sunday report on the effects of the 
strike said the situation in stepanakert was red hot and that 
people were hiding at home rather than going to work 
during the strike factories stood idle transport did not run 
and railway cars carrying foodstuffs remained unloaded trud said 
it said the strike had cost the region about 50 million in losses 
in nonindustrial goods alone 
trud said the strike had been a stab in the back for 
perestroika mikhail s gorbachevs program for economic and 
social restructuring 
