laos held its first nationwide 
elections sunday since the communists seized power in that 
southeast asian nation 13 years ago the official laotian news 
agency kpl said 
the agency report monitored in bangkok said voters cast 
ballots for 4462 candidates running for 2410 seat on 
districtlevel peoples councils 
the district elections are to be followed in midnovember by 
those at provincial and national levels while village elections are 
to take place later according to laotian officials 
the elections appear to be another sign of greater openness in 
laos over the past year the government has promoted 
capitaliststyle reforms of the economy and plans to decentralize 
the bureaucracy 
the agency said 1793000 eligible voters representing 47 
percent of the population cast secret ballots in the nations 113 
districts 
the highestlevel elections will be for 79 seats in the supreme 
peoples assembly which was formed dec 2 1975 and assigned to 
draft a constitution and prepare the country for elections 
laotian official are unclear as to why it has taken so long for 
the elections to be held the constitution is not expected to be 
completed until next year 
real power in laos still rests with the communist party and its 
highest body the politburo the poliburo is led by kaysone 
phomvihane who fought the french colonialists and then led the 
guerrilla war against the usbacked vientiane government that 
fell in 1975 
