<TEXT>
the foreign ministers of seven leading 
latin american nations stated sunday that the 8 billion in 
outstanding mutual debt among their nations was the main obstacle 
to creating a regional common market 
foreign ministers of the group of eight mexico brazil 
argentina venezuela colombia uruguay and peru issued a 
communique at the end of their weekend meeting saying they agreed 
to work together to find a solution to the problem 
group member panama was absent from the meeting panama was 
suspended from the group at its last meeting in february shortly 
after military leader gen manuel antonio noriega was indicted in 
the united states on drug trafficking charges noriega engineered 
the ouster of president eric arturo delvalle after delvalle tried 
to fire him 
the ministers who also spent much of their time working on an 
agenda for a summit meeting of their presidents later this year 
offered no specifics about that meeting 
latin american leaders have talked of a common market for years 
but earlier attempts at economic integration have failed 
in the 1960s a central american common market and an 11nation 
latin american free trade association were formed but later broke 
apart amid civil wars and squabbling over tariffs 
recently the group of eight has been trying to revive the plan 
spurned on the economic stagnation blamed in part on the regions 
massive foreign debts last year for example argentina brazil 
and uruguay signed accords breaking down trade barriers 
it is necessary to create mechanisms that will allow the 
nations of latin america to develop in the medium and longterm 
said mexican foreign ministry spokesman victor flores olea 
the ministers also agreed that latin american nations should 
take the most concerted position possible in confronting their 
international lenders 
on monday the ministers will meet in mexico city turning their 
attention to the problems of central america and panamas status in 
the group 
they are to meet with president miguel de la madrid and with 
panamas foreign minister jorge ritter 
 
